*International Space Station* (for some reason) makes it sound enormous, but
even tremendous things are hard to spot from 542 km (337 mi) away. At that
distance, the station appears 1/60th the size of the width of your pinky finger
held at arm's length—51 arcseconds wide.

The picture above is a composite of six photographs, each taken within a single
second.

Equipment:

* [Nikon D610](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nikon_D610)
* [iOptron skyguider pro](https://www.ioptron.com/product-p/3550.htm)
* [iOptron tripod](https://www.ioptron.com/product-p/3221.htm)
* [Sigma 150-600mm 5-6.3 Contemporary](https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00THP1A1C?psc=1&ref=ppx_yo2_dt_b_product_details)
* Cheap intervalometer
* [Thousand Oaks solar film](https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00DS7SSEW?psc=1&ref=ppx_yo2_dt_b_product_details) ([gaffer's taped](https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00GZE3UJ8/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_search_asin_title?ie=UTF8&psc=1) over my lens hood)

Software

* [transit-finder.com](https://transit-finder.com/)
* [SkEye](https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.lavadip.skeye) (for polar alignment during the daytime—point at σ-Octantis!)
* [AtomicClock](https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=partl.atomicclock) for accurate time
* [Ventusky](https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=cz.ackee.ventusky) + [skippysky](https://www.skippysky.com.au/) + [clear dark sky](https://www.cleardarksky.com/csk/) for cloud reports

